              "id": 222,
              "action": "<p>\n English\n <a href=\"https://www.catholic.org/encyclopedia/view.php?id=7650\">\n  martyr\n </a>\n from Dunmow, Essex. The daughter of William Heigham, she was disowned by him when she married a Catholic, Roger Line. Roger was imprisoned for being a\n <a href=\"https://www.catholic.org/encyclopedia/view.php?id=2678\">\n  Catholic\n </a>\n and was exiled and died in 1594 in Flanders, Belgium. Anne stayed in England where she hid\n <a href=\"https://www.catholic.org/encyclopedia/view.php?id=2678\">\n  Catholic\n </a>\n priests in a London safe house. In this endeavor she aided Jesuit Father\n <a href=\"https://www.catholic.org/bible/book.php?id=50\">\n  John\n </a>\n Gerard until her arrest. Anne was hanged in Tyburn on February 27, 1601. Pope Paul VI canonized Anne Line in 1970 as one of the\n <a href=\"https://www.catholic.org/encyclopedia/view.php?id=4797\">\n  Forty Martyrs\n </a>\n of England and Wales.\n</p>\n",
