              "action": "<p>\n According to tradition, Hallvard was a Norwegian, son of Vebjorn of Husaby. He became a trader in the Baltic Islands. While defending a\n <a href=\"https://www.catholic.org/encyclopedia/view.php?id=12437\">\n  woman\n </a>\n who bought\n <a href=\"https://www.catholic.org/encyclopedia/view.php?id=10430\">\n  sanctuary\n </a>\n on his ship from three men accusing her of\n <a href=\"https://www.catholic.org/encyclopedia/view.php?id=11428\">\n  theft\n </a>\n (he offered to make\n <a href=\"https://www.catholic.org/encyclopedia/view.php?id=9970\">\n  restitution\n </a>\n to them), he was killed, with the woman, by arrows from the men. Though they attached a stone to his body when they cast it into the sea, it came to the surface, and the whole story came out. He has long been revered as a\n <a href=\"https://www.catholic.org/encyclopedia/view.php?id=7650\">\n  martyr\n </a>\n for his defense of an innocent\n <a href=\"https://www.catholic.org/encyclopedia/view.php?id=9193\">\n  person\n </a>\n and is the patron saint of Oslo. His\n <a href=\"https://www.catholic.org/saints/f_day/\">\n  feast day\n </a>\n is May 15.\n</p>\n",
