              "id": 612,
              "action": "<p>\n Feast day: June 09: Anne\n <a href=\"https://www.catholic.org/bookstore/?category=19\">\n  Mary\n </a>\n Taigi (1769 - 1837) Born at Siena, daughter of a druggist named Giannetti, whose  business failed, she was brought to\n <a href=\"https://www.catholic.org/encyclopedia/view.php?id=10148\">\n  Rome\n </a>\n and worked for a\n <a href=\"https://www.catholic.org/encyclopedia/view.php?id=11571\">\n  time\n </a>\n as a domestic servant. In 1790 she married Dominic Taigi, a butler of the Chigi\n <a href=\"https://www.catholic.org/encyclopedia/view.php?id=4568\">\n  family\n </a>\n in Rome, and lived the normal\n <a href=\"https://www.catholic.org/encyclopedia/view.php?id=7101\">\n  life\n </a>\n of a married\n <a href=\"https://www.catholic.org/encyclopedia/view.php?id=12437\">\n  woman\n </a>\n of the working class. In the discharge of these humble duties and in the bringing up of her seven\n <a href=\"https://www.catholic.org/shopping/?category=28\">\n  children\n </a>\n she attained a high degree of holiness. Endowed with the gift of prophecy, she read thoughts and described distant events. Her home became the rendezvous of cardinals and other dignitaries who sought her counsel. She was\n <a href=\"https://www.catholic.org/saints\">\n  beatified\n </a>\n in 1920.\n</p>\n",
