              "action": "<p>\n St. Januarius was born in\n <a href=\"https://www.catholic.org/encyclopedia/view.php?id=6217\">\n  Italy\n </a>\n and was\n <a href=\"https://www.catholic.org/encyclopedia/view.php?id=1918\">\n  bishop\n </a>\n of Benevento during the Emperor Diocletion persecution.\n <a href=\"https://www.catholic.org/encyclopedia/view.php?id=1918\">\n  Bishop\n </a>\n Januarius went to visit two\n <a href=\"https://www.catholic.org/encyclopedia/view.php?id=3690\">\n  deacons\n </a>\n and two laymen in prison. He was then also imprison along with his deacon and lector. They were thrown to the wild beasts, but when the animals did not attack them, they were beheaded. What is believed to be Januarius' blood is kept in Naples, as a relic. It liquifies and bubbles when exposed in the cathedral. Scientists have not been able to explain this\n <a href=\"https://www.catholic.org/encyclopedia/view.php?id=8016\">\n  miracle\n </a>\n to date.\n <a href=\"https://www.catholic.org/saints/saint.php?saint_id=355\">\n  St. Januarius\n </a>\n lived and died around 305 A.D. and his\n <a href=\"https://www.catholic.org/saints/f_day/\">\n  feast day\n </a>\n is September 19th.\n</p>\n",
